{# templates/roadmaps/stock/market-volatility.html.twig #}
{% extends 'base-roadmaps.html.twig' %}

{% block stylesheets %}
    {{ parent() }}
    {{ encore_entry_link_tags('stock_css') }}
{% endblock %}

{% block javascripts %}
    {{ parent() }}
    {{ encore_entry_script_tags('stock_js') }}
{% endblock %}

{% block body %}
    <div class="container">
        <!-- article hero – stock style -->
        <div class="article-hero animate">
            <div class="hero-content">
                <div class="hero-icon" style="background-color: var(--stocks-accent);">
                    <i class="fas fa-wave-square"></i>
                </div>
                <h1>Market Volatility <span>How to Stay Calm During Dips</span></h1>
                <p class="hero-description">
                    Market ups and downs are normal. Learn what causes volatility, how to prepare for it, and why staying invested is often the best strategy.
                </p>
                <div class="phase-tag">
                    <i class="fas fa-layer-group"></i> Phase 2: Risk Management · 10 min read
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- introduction -->
        <section class="animate">
            <h2 class="section-title">🌊 What Is Market Volatility?</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; margin-bottom: 20px;">
                <strong>Volatility</strong> refers to the speed and magnitude of price changes in a market. High volatility means prices can swing sharply in either direction over a short period. It's often measured by the VIX (fear index) or standard deviation.
            </p>
            <p style="font-size: 1.1rem; color: var(--gray-color);">
                Volatility is not the same as risk. Risk is the chance of permanent loss; volatility is just price fluctuation. For long‑term investors, volatility can be an opportunity to buy at lower prices.
            </p>
        </section>

        <!-- why markets get volatile -->
        <div class="card animate" style="margin: 40px 0;">
            <h3 style="font-size: 1.8rem; margin-bottom: 20px;">⚡ Why Does Volatility Happen?</h3>
            <ul style="margin-left: 20px;">
                <li><strong>Economic data:</strong> Jobs reports, inflation, GDP surprises.</li>
                <li><strong>Geopolitical events:</strong> Wars, elections, trade disputes.</li>
                <li><strong>Corporate earnings:</strong> Companies missing or beating expectations.</li>
                <li><strong>Market sentiment:</strong> Fear and greed drive short‑term moves.</li>
                <li><strong>Liquidity changes:</strong> Central bank policies, interest rates.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- staying calm strategies -->
        <div class="rule-grid animate">
            <div class="rule-item">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-brain"></i> 1. Know Your Time Horizon</h4>
                <p>If you don't need the money for years, short‑term drops don't matter. Historically, markets always recovered.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rule-item">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> 2. Ignore the Noise</h4>
                <p>Turn off financial TV. Stick to your plan. Emotional decisions often lead to selling low and buying high.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rule-item">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-coins"></i> 3. Keep Investing (DCA)</h4>
                <p>Dollar‑cost averaging during downturns buys more shares at lower prices, boosting long‑term returns.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="rule-item">
                <h4><i class="fas fa-umbrella"></i> 4. Have a Cash Buffer</h4>
                <p>An emergency fund prevents you from selling stocks at the worst time to cover expenses.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- interactive tool: Market Recovery Simulator -->
        <div class="card animate" style="margin: 40px 0;" id="volatility-simulator">
            <h3><i class="fas fa-chart-line"></i> Market Recovery Simulator</h3>
            <p>See how a market drop affects your portfolio and how long it could take to recover based on different return assumptions.</p>

            <div style="display: flex; flex-wrap: wrap; gap: 20px; margin: 20px 0;">
                <div style="flex: 1 1 200px;">
                    <label style="display: block; font-weight: 600;">Current portfolio value ($)</label>
                    <input type="number" id="currentValue" class="cat-input" value="10000" min="0" step="1000">
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 1 1 200px;">
                    <label style="display: block; font-weight: 600;">Market drop (%)</label>
                    <input type="number" id="dropPercent" class="cat-input" value="30" min="0" max="100" step="1">
                </div>
                <div style="flex: 1 1 200px;">
                    <label style="display: block; font-weight: 600;">Expected annual return after drop (%)</label>
                    <input type="number" id="futureReturn" class="cat-input" value="8" min="0" max="30" step="0.5">
                </div>
            </div>

            <div style="margin-top: 20px;">
                <button id="calculateRecovery" class="btn-outline">Calculate Recovery Time</button>
            </div>

            <div id="recoveryResult" style="margin-top: 25px; padding: 20px; background: var(--light-color); border-radius: 12px;">
                Enter values and click calculate.
            </div>

            <p class="pro-tip" style="margin-top: 15px; background-color: #e6f7f0; border-left-color: var(--stocks-accent);">
                <i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> This is a simplified projection. Actual market returns are never guaranteed, and recovery times vary.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- quiz section (conditional) -->
        {% if app.user and quiz is defined and quiz %}
            {# Logged in user – quiz already taken #}
            <div class="quiz-container animate">
                <h3 style="color:white; margin-top: 0;">🧠 You've already taken this quiz</h3>
                <p style="color: #e2e8f0; font-size: 1.2rem;">
                    Your score: <strong>{{ quiz.quizzScore }}%</strong>
                </p>
                <p style="color: #cbd5e0;">
                    You can retake the quiz to improve your score. Click the button below to reset it.
                </p>
                <div class="quiz-actions">
                    <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'stock', slug: 'market-volatility', retake: 1 }) }}"
                       class="btn"
                       style="background-color: #0e9f6e; color: white; text-decoration: none;">
                        Retake Quiz
                    </a>
                </div>
            </div>
        {% else %}
            {# Show quiz (interactivity blocked by JS if not logged in) #}
            <div class="quiz-container animate" data-page-id="{{ page.id }}">
                <h3 style="color:white; margin-top: 0;">📝 Test your knowledge: Market Volatility</h3>

                <div class="quiz-question">1. What is market volatility?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="1">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">The total return of the market</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">The speed and magnitude of price fluctuations</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">The dividend yield of stocks</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">The number of companies in an index</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">2. A market decline of 10% or more is called a:</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="2">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Bear market</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">Correction</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Crash</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Recession</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">3. Which of the following is a good strategy during a market downturn?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="3">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Sell everything to avoid further losses</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">Continue investing through dollar‑cost averaging</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Move all money to cash permanently</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Only buy stocks that have gone up</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">4. Historically, after major market crashes, the market has:</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="4">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Never recovered</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Taken exactly 5 years to recover</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">Always recovered and reached new highs over time</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Become more volatile permanently</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-question">5. Why is having an emergency fund important during volatile markets?</div>
                <div class="quiz-options" data-question="5">
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">To buy more stocks at the bottom</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="correct">So you don't have to sell investments at a loss to cover expenses</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">To earn higher interest</div>
                    <div class="quiz-option" data-answer="wrong">Because stocks are too risky</div>
                </div>

                <div class="quiz-actions">
                    <button id="quiz-submit" class="btn">Get score & submit</button>
                </div>
                <div class="quiz-result"></div>
            </div>
        {% endif %}

        <!-- next steps in phase 2 (risk management) -->
        <section style="margin: 60px 0;">
            <h2 class="section-title" style="text-align: center;">📘 Continue Phase 2: Risk Management</h2>
            <div class="next-steps">
                <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'stock', slug: 'diversification' }) }}" class="next-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-random"></i>
                    <h3>Diversification</h3>
                    <p>Spread risk across different assets.</p>
                </a>
                <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'stock', slug: 'asset-allocation' }) }}" class="next-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-scale-balanced"></i>
                    <h3>Asset Allocation</h3>
                    <p>Find the right mix for your goals.</p>
                </a>
                <a href="{{ path('app_page_show', { journey: 'stock', slug: 'risk-tolerance' }) }}" class="next-card">
                    <i class="fas fa-heartbeat"></i>
                    <h3>Risk Tolerance</h3>
                    <p>Know your comfort zone.</p>
                </a>
            </div>
        </section>
    </div>
{% endblock %}
